-- French Stocks Are Little Changed; Burelle, Electricite de France, Hermes
-- B y   A l e x i s   X y d i a s
-- 2010-10-25T15:50:35Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-25/french-stocks-atos-origin-edf-lvmh-hermes-international-rhodia-move.html
France’s  CAC 40 Index  increased less
than 0.1 percent to 3,870 at 5:43 p.m. in Paris. The SBF 120
Index climbed 0.3 percent to 2,892.2.  The following shares rose or fell in the French capital.
Stock symbols are in parentheses.       Burelle SA  (BUR FP) rose 5 percent to 169 euros. The
company forecast that 2010 sales will rise 30 percent to 3.2
billion euros ($4.5 billion). Sales growth will continue in
2011, the company said in a statement on Hugin.  Catering International & Services SA  (CTRG FP) rose 3
percent to 59.64 euros. The catering-services group that
operates in 38 countries said third-quarter sales climbed to 54
million euros from 39.1 million euros a year earlier. The
company forecast full-year sales rising at least 10 percent.  Electricite de France SA  (EDF FP), the country’s biggest
power company, jumped 1.8 percent to 32.44 euros. France may
raise electricity prices by 3 percent to 4 percent at the start
of 2011, daily Les Echos reported, without citing anyone.  Hermes International SCA  (RMS FP) soared 15 percent to
202.85 euros, its steepest gain since October 2008.  LVMH Moet
Hennessy Louis Vuitton SA  (MC FP) gained 2.4 percent to 116
euros, the biggest advance in the CAC 40. The world’s largest
maker of luxury goods said it intends to raise its stake in
Hermes to 17.1 percent after buying 14 percent. LVMH, which paid
about 80.5 euros per Hermes share, doesn’t plan on taking
control of its rival.       Rhodia SA  (RHA FP) gained 4.1 percent to 20.99 euros, its
sixth advance and the longest winning streak since July. The
chemicals company aims to double its sales in Asia to 2 billion
euros a year by 2015, Les Echos reported, citing Chief Executive
Officer  Jean-Pierre Clamadieu .  To contact the reporters on this story:
Alexis Xydias in London at 
 axydias@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editors responsible for this story:
